<paper id="1843935160"><title>Extended Symbolic Projections as a Knowledge Structure for Spatial Reasoning</title><year>1988</year><authors><author org="FOA, National Defence Research Institute" id="2974307008">Erland Jungert</author></authors><n_citation>48</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1598864366</reference><reference>2022178031</reference></references><venue id="1131605622" type="C">International Conference on Pattern Recognition</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-19036-8_34</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.47487">The Symbolic</keyword><keyword weight="0.42946">Computer vision</keyword><keyword weight="0.66092">Knowledge representation and reasoning</keyword><keyword weight="0.57448">Spatial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.44619">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Knowledge structure</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.45914">Natural language processing</keyword><keyword weight="0.672">Reasoning system</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Spatial knowledge</keyword><keyword weight="0.64587">Qualitative reasoning</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In earlier work it has been demonstrated that symbolic projections can be used as a spatial knowledge structure. Here it will be shown how the basic language used in the symbolic projections can be extended. The motivation for this extension is the need for a means by which to perform spatial reasoning in, e.g. digitized images or maps.</abstract></paper>